        <p>These programs were designed for families under financial pressure — which is most single-parent households at some point. Using them isn't a failure; it's using a resource you and every other working person has paid into. Here's what's actually available.</p>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>Yes, dads qualify.</strong> Many of these programs are associated with mothers in people's minds, but they are available to any custodial or primary caregiver parent, including fathers. Don't assume you're excluded — apply and find out.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>SNAP (food assistance)</h2>
        <p>The Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program — formerly food stamps — helps cover grocery costs. As of 2024, the average benefit is around $180/month per person in a qualifying household.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Who qualifies:</strong> income-based. Generally, households earning under 130% of the federal poverty level qualify. For a family of three, that's roughly $2,900/month gross income or less, though limits vary by state.</li>
          <li><strong>How to apply:</strong> through your state's SNAP agency — usually the Department of Social Services or Health and Human Services. Many states allow online applications.</li>
          <li><strong>What it covers:</strong> groceries (bread, meat, dairy, produce, canned goods). Not alcohol, tobacco, vitamins, or hot prepared food.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>WIC (food for young kids and infants)</h2>
        <p>The Women, Infants, and Children program covers specific healthy foods for children under 5 and for pregnant or nursing parents. The name is outdated — fathers who are the primary caregiver for a child under 5 do qualify.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Who qualifies:</strong> income-based (up to 185% of poverty level), and the child must be under 5 (or an infant, or you must be pregnant/nursing).</li>
          <li><strong>What it covers:</strong> formula, milk, eggs, juice, cereal, fruits and vegetables, whole grains, and peanut butter — specific items vary by state.</li>
          <li><strong>How to apply:</strong> through your local WIC agency. Find yours at <a href="https://www.fns.usda.gov/wic/wic-how-apply" target="_blank" rel="noopener">fns.usda.gov/wic</a>.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>CHIP (children's health insurance)</h2>
        <p>The Children's Health Insurance Program covers kids whose families earn too much for Medicaid but can't afford private insurance. Coverage is comprehensive — doctor visits, prescriptions, dental, vision.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Who qualifies:</strong> varies by state, but generally households up to 200–300% of the poverty level. That's a significant range — in many states, a family of three earning up to $60,000+ can qualify.</li>
          <li><strong>How to apply:</strong> through your state's Medicaid/CHIP agency, or at <a href="https://www.healthcare.gov/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">healthcare.gov</a>.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Childcare assistance (CCAP)</h2>
        <p>The Child Care and Development Fund (CCDF) — sometimes called CCAP, Child Care Assistance Program, or similar names depending on your state — helps pay for daycare, after-school care, and in-home care while you work or attend school.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Who qualifies:</strong> working, job-searching, or enrolled in school parents below a state-set income limit. Limits vary significantly — check your state's program.</li>
          <li><strong>How to apply:</strong> through your state childcare agency. Start at <a href="https://childcare.gov/consumer-education/get-help-paying-for-child-care" target="_blank" rel="noopener">childcare.gov</a> for a state-by-state directory.</li>
          <li><strong>Waitlists:</strong> demand is high in many areas. Apply as early as possible — some states have long waitlists.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Housing assistance</h2>
        <p>Federal housing programs can significantly reduce rent, but they are heavily subscribed. Still worth applying — circumstances change and lists move.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Section 8 / Housing Choice Voucher:</strong> subsidizes rent in private housing. Apply through your local Public Housing Authority (PHA). Find yours at <a href="https://www.hud.gov/program_offices/public_indian_housing/pha/contacts" target="_blank" rel="noopener">hud.gov</a>. Waitlists are common — apply and keep your application current.</li>
          <li><strong>Public housing:</strong> government-owned units at subsidized rent. Same application process via your local PHA.</li>
          <li><strong>Emergency rental assistance:</strong> if you're at risk of eviction, your county or city may have an Emergency Rental Assistance Program (ERAP). Search "[your county] emergency rental assistance" — many are still active.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>LIHEAP (utility bills)</h2>
        <p>The Low Income Home Energy Assistance Program helps pay heating and cooling bills. Applied for through your state — search "[your state] LIHEAP" to find your local agency.</p>

        <h2>The quickest way to find what you qualify for</h2>
        <p>Rather than applying to each program individually, two tools can screen you for multiple programs at once:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="https://www.benefits.gov/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">benefits.gov</a> — official federal benefits screener covering 1,000+ programs. Enter your situation and it returns what you likely qualify for.</li>
          <li><a href="https://www.findhelp.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">findhelp.org</a> — searches local nonprofit and government resources by zip code. Good for finding things benefits.gov misses.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>Apply even if you're not sure you qualify.</strong> Eligibility is more generous than most people assume, and the worst outcome is a rejection — which costs you nothing but the time to apply. Many dads who needed help never asked because they assumed they wouldn't qualify.</p>
        </div>

        <p>Once you're stabilized, the <a href="{{ '/financial/budgeting/' | url }}">Budgeting guide</a> covers how to build a system that keeps you there. And if custody costs are a specific pressure point, see <a href="{{ '/financial/funding-custody/' | url }}">Funding a Custody Case</a>.</p>

        <p><em>Program details, income limits, and eligibility rules change. Verify current details directly with the program before applying.</em></p>
